        <section id="tip-html">
            <h2 class="tip-heading">HTML</h2>
            <ol class="tips-list">
                <li>To know when to use bold tags read from these sources
                    <span class="tip-source">Sources: <a
                            href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2243074/is-it-ok-to-use-strong-in-place-of-b-blindly">Source
                            1</a>, <a href="https://html.com/tags/b/">Source 2</a>, <a
                            href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/649305/alternative-to-the-html-bold-tag#:~:text=If%20you%20don%27t%20want%20to%20stress%20importance%2C%20use,make%20sense%20to%20have%20an%20entire%20paragraph%20emphasized.">Source
                            3</a></span>
                </li>
                <li>If you want to preserve whitespace in your document then use <code>&ltpre></code> tag around your
                    text
                    whose whitespace you want to be intact. You can also use CSS selector { white-space: pre; } to do
                    the
                    same. <span class="tip-source">Sources: <a
                            href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8994516/html-css-best-practice-for-preserving-white-space-on-certain-elements">StackOverflow</a>,
                        <a
                            href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/9492249/render-a-string-in-html-and-preserve-spaces-and-linebreaks">StackOverflow</a>
                    </span></li>
                <li>You can use &amplt to actually display tags like <code>&ltb></code> without browser rendering it. If
                    you
                    want to
                    display that what you are writing is actually an HTML code use <code>&ltcode></code> tag and if you
                    want
                    to preserve
                    whitespace of your code then use <code>&ltpre></code> tag as well. Do not use
                    <code>&lttextarea></code>
                    or
                    <code>&ltxmp></code> to display the tags as they might break in some conditions.<span
                        class="tip-source">Sources: <a
                            href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2820453/display-html-snippets-in-html">StackOverflow</a>,
                        <a href="https://www.webmasterworld.com/forum13/3900.htm">Source2</a></span>
                </li>
                <li>Do not use heading elements for subheadings. <span class="tip-source">Sources: <a
                            href="https://www.w3.org/TR/2014/CR-html5-20140204/common-idioms.html#sub-head">Source1</a>
                    </span> </li>
                <li>A section may have a heading of it's own and might contain nested sections and articles within it.
                </li>
                <li>Certain elements called root sectioning elements have section outlines of their own and they do not
                    interfere with the section outline of their ancestor section elements - body,blockquote,td are some
                    of
                    these elements.</li>
                <li>Sectioning content elements are considered subsections of nearest root sectioning element or any
                    other
                    sectioning content element.</li>
                <li>h1â€“h6 elements must not be used to markup subheadings, subtitles, alternative titles and taglines
                    unless
                    intended to be the heading for a new section or subsection. <span class="tip-source">Sources: <a
                            href="https://www.w3.org/TR/html52/common-idioms-without-dedicated-elements.html#common-idioms-without-dedicated-elements">Source
                            1</a></span></li>
                <li>When you place two or more inline/inline-block elements who don't have any padding or
                    margin of their own in separate lines in your HTML markup then you might end up with whitespace
                    between
                    two elements, this is because inline elements respects the whitespace in the markup. You can read
                    about
                    these on Stackoverflow <a
                        href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19038799/why-is-there-an-unexplainable-gap-between-these-inline-block-div-elements">Post1</a>
                    <a
                        href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5078239/how-do-i-remove-the-space-between-inline-inline-block-elements">Post2</a>
                    to know how to work around this.
                </li>
                <li>If you want to have a default value for options or kind of a placeholder, then read this <a
                        href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3518002/how-can-i-set-the-default-value-for-an-html-select-element">post</a>
                    on Stackoveflow.</li>
            </ol>
